    "abstract": "<jats:p>\n                  For Germany it is predicted that the first wave of the corona pandemic disease reaches its maximum of new infections on April 11th, 2020\n                  <jats:inline-formula>\n                    <jats:alternatives>\n                      <jats:inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"20048942v1_inline1.gif\"/>\n                    </jats:alternatives>\n                  </jats:inline-formula>\n                  days with 90 percent confidence. With a delay of about 7 days the maximum demand on breathing machines in hospitals occurs on April 18th, 2020\n                  <jats:inline-formula>\n                    <jats:alternatives>\n                      <jats:inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xlink:href=\"20048942v1_inline2.gif\"/>\n                    </jats:alternatives>\n                  </jats:inline-formula>\n                  days. The first pandemic wave ends in Germany end of May 2020. The predictions are based on the assumption of a Gaussian time evolution well justified by the central limit theorem of statistics. The width and the maximum time and thus the duration of this Gaussian distribution are determined from a statistical\n                  <jats:italic>\u03c7</jats:italic>\n                  <jats:sup>2</jats:sup>\n                  -fit to the observed doubling times before March 28, 2020.\n                </jats:p>",
